title: Alpha particle induced reactions on 151Eu: Possibility of production of 152Tb radioisotope for PET imaging

x4freetext: Alpha particle induced reactions on 151Eu:
Possibility of production of 152Tb radioisotope for
PET imaging

x4codes.hlp: Joint Institute for Nuclear Research (JINR), Dubna

x4freetext: U-150 isochronous cyclotron
The stacks consisted of 20 targets. Each target was a
thin 151Eu layer with a thickness of ~100 mu-g/cm2
and a spot diameter of 22 mm, electrochemically
deposited on the surface of a titanium foil with a
thickness of 2 mu-m. Eu2O3 with enrichment of 97.5 +
-0.1%, with impurity content of 0.02% Nd, 0.02% Gd,
<0.01% Sm provided by the state reserve of stable
isotopes was used for electrode-position.
Ultrapure germanium detector with an energy
resolution of 850 eV for the 122 keV line and 1.8 keV
for the 1.33 MeV line was used for gamma
spectrometry. The distance from the source to the
detector was 6 or 11 cm, depending on the radiation
intensity, and was chosen so that the dead time did
not exceed 10-15%.
Aluminum foils with a thickness of 9 to 100 mu-m
were placed between the targets, serving as beam
monitors or degraders.
The irradiation time was about 30 min, the
average beam current was ~ 1.7 mu-A. Measurements of
radioactivity were started 4 h after EOB in the first
experiment (60 MeV) and after 24 h in the second (43
MeV), and were repeated several times during the
week to determine the activity of radionuclides with
different half-lives. Typical acquisition time was
The uncertainty in measuring the beam energy was
estimated as + -1 MeV. The uncertainty of the
thickness of the absorbers and monitor was determined
by multiple weighing and was estimated as 0.1-1 mu-m,
depending on the foil mass. The calculated total
energy uncertainty was 1-1.7 MeV, depending on the
position of the target in the stack.
The uncertainty was calculated as the square
root of the sum of the squares of the individual
uncertainties:
uncertainty for the detector efficiency;
uncertainty for the target thickness;
uncertainty for nuclear data;
uncertainty for the current value.
Entry was approved by Dr. A.N. Moiseeva
Energy units in Sub002-006 were corrected.
